 [[The CW]] by [[Warner Bros. Television]] and [[Berlanti Productions]], with a planned release in the 2018\u201319 television season. The series would be a companion series to ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]''. [[Lee Toland Krieger]] would direct the pilot, which would be written by [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]]. Both are executive producers along with [[Greg Berlanti]], [[Sarah Schechter]], and Jon Goldwater.<ref name=\"SeriesAnnounce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/riverdale-sabrina-companion-series-works-at-cw-1041527|title='Riverdale' Companion Series 'The Chilling Adventures of Sabrina' In the Works at The CW|last=Stanhope|first=Kate|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=September 20, 2017}}</ref> In December 2017, the project had moved to [[Netflix]] under a yet-to-be-announced new title. Two seasons, comprising ten episodes each, have been ordered by the streaming service;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/sabrina-the-teenage-witch-series-picked-up-netflix-2-season-order-1202218168/|title=Sabrina The Teenage Witch Series Picked Up By Netflix With 2-Season Order|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 1, 2017|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref> this was later altered to be one, 20-episode season split across two parts.<ref name=\"SeasonTwoVariety\" /><ref name=\"SeasonTwoTVLine\" /> CW President Mark Pedowitz stated that Netflix's ability to offer a two-season commitment enticed Warner Bros. Television to move the series to the streaming service.<ref name=\"PedowtizJan2018\" /> In early May 2018, ''Chilling Adventures of Sabrina'' was officially confirmed as the series' title.<ref name=\"TitleConfirm\">{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/05/02/sabrina-teenage-witch-netflix-reboot-title/|title=Sabrina the Teenage Witch reboot gets title \u2014 and first official look at its adorable star|last=Lawrence|first=Derek|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=May 2, 2018|accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref> The series was inspired by \"slow-burn horror\" films such as ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'', ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'', and other \"great satanic horror movies from the 1960s and 1970s\".<ref name=\"EWSep2018\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/09/13/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-preview-kiernan-shipka/|title=Chilling Adventures of Sabrina cast previews a darker show than you might expect|last=Highfill|first=Samantha|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=September 13, 2018|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref> The opening title sequence features the art of Robert Hack, the original artist of the comic book series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/10/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-netflix-opening-credits.html|title=How Chilling Adventures of Sabrina Made Its Creepy Opening Credits|website=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]|last=Riesman|first=Abraham|date=October 26, 2018|accessdate=December 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 12, 2018, Netflix announced that the eleventh episode of the twenty episodes ordered would be released as a [[Christmas special]] episode.<ref name=\"HolidaySpecial\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/chilling-adventures-sabrina-gets-a-holiday-special-netflix-1160310 |title='Chilling Adventures of Sabrina' Gets a Holiday Special on Netflix |last=Porter |first=Rick |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=November 12, 2018 |accessdate=November 12, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112192638/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/chilling-adventures-sabrina-gets-a-holiday-special-netflix-1160310 |archivedate=November 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Special11thEpisode\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-christmas-episode.html|title=''Chilling Adventures of Sabrina'' Is Getting a Surprise Christmas Episode|last=Adalian|first=Josef|website=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]|date=November 12, 2018|accessdate=November 13, 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113070409/https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-christmas-episode.html|archivedate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> It was not always the plan for the series to have a Christmas-themed episode. During production of the first episode of the second part, Aguirre-Sacasa realized that the series had already done episodes related to Halloween and Thanksgiving in the first part, and decided to create the episode. He noted the episode \"was by and large self-contained, but that there are still elements that carry it through and the realizations and relationships and mythology \u2014 it sort of threads the needle. And so we figured out a story that could do both.\" The episode was also helpful for Netflix, who wanted some sort of additional, standalone content to release between the first two parts.<ref name=\"ChristmasSpecialWrap\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-holiday-episode-so-quick-midwinters-tale-netflix/|title='Chilling Adventures of Sabrina': Here's How They Turned the Holiday Episode Around So Quickly|last=Maas|first=Jennifer|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|date=December 9, 2018|accessdate=December 22, 2018}}</ref> On December 18, 2018, Netflix renewed the series for a second season of 16 episodes, which will also be split into two parts.<ref name=\"SeasonTwoVariety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-renewed-netflix-1203092148/|title='Chilling Adventures of Sabrina' Renewed for Season 2 at Netflix|last=Otterson|first=Joe|date=December 18, 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"SeasonTwoTVLine\">{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2018/12/18/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-renewed-season-3-4-netflix/|title=Chilling Adventures of Sabrina Renewed for 'Parts' 3 and 4 at Netflix|last=Iannucci|first=Rebecca|work=[[TVLine]]|date=December 18, 2018|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nIn January 2018, [[Kiernan Shipka]] was cast as [[Sabrina Spellman]].<ref name=\"Shipka\" /> Shipka was Aguirre-Sacasa's first choice for the role.<ref name=\"EWSep2018\" /> The next month, [[Jaz Sinclair]] was cast as Rosalind \"Roz\" Walker,<ref name=\"Sinclair\" /> along with [[Michelle Gomez]] as [[Madam Satan (comics)|Mary Wardwell / Madam Satan]], [[Chance Perdomo]] as Ambrose Spellman,<ref name=\"GomezPerdomo\" /> [[Lucy Davis]] as [[Hilda Spellman]],<ref name=\"Davis\" /> [[Miranda Otto]] as [[Zelda Spellman]],<ref name=\"Otto\" /> and [[Richard Coyle]] as Father Faustus Blackwood.<ref name=\"Coyle\" /> In March 2018, [[Ross Lynch]] joined the cast as Harvey Kinkle,<ref name=\"Lynch\" /> while [[Tati Gabrielle]] was cast as Prudence Night.<ref name=\"Gabrielle\" /> In early March 2018, [[Bronson Pinchot]], Adeline Rudolph, and Abigail Cowen, were cast as George Hawthorne, Agatha, and Dorcas, respectively.<ref name=\"Pinchot\" /><ref name=\"RudolphCowenTHR\" /> In November 2018, it was revealed that [[Alexis Denisof]] and Jedidiah Goodacre would join the cast in the second part in the recurring roles of Adam Masters and Dorian Gray, respectively, while [[Mckenna Grace]] would portray a young Sabrina in the [[Christmas special]] episode.<ref name=\"McKennaDenisofGoodacre\" />\n\nIn June 2019, it was reported that [[Lachlan Watson]] and [[Gavin Leatherwood]] had been promoted to the main cast for the second season.<ref name=\"LW&GL\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-ups-gavin-leatherwood-lachlan-watson-to-series-regulars-1202627743/|title='Chilling Adventures Of Sabrina' Ups Gavin Leatherwood & Lachlan Watson To Series Regulars|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=June 6, 2019|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, Sam Corlett, Skye Marshall, and Jonathan Whitesell were cast in recurring roles for part 3 of the series.<ref name=\"Part3AddRecur\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-adds-three-to-cast-for-season-3-of-netflix-series-1202813365/|title='Chilling Adventures Of Sabrina' Adds Three To Cast For Season 3 Of Netflix Series|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nFilming for the first part began on March 19, 2018, just as filming of the second season of ''Riverdale'' concluded, which allowed the same crew members to work on both series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/television/hollywood-north-magical-time-for-vancouver-tv-production|title=Hollywood North: Magical time for Vancouver TV production|last=Brown|first=Scott|website=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> The first two parts were filmed back-to-back,<ref name=\"THRFilming\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/riverdale-shoot-sabrina-moves-netflix-2-season-order-1060852|title='Riverdale' Offshoot 'Sabrina' Moves to Netflix With 2-Season Order|last=Goldberg|first=Leslie|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 1, 2017|accessdate=January 26, 2018}}</ref> with filming on the second part concluding on December 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dgc.ca/assets/Uploads/BritishColumbia/AvailsProductionLists/Documents/Production-List.pdf |title=DGC BC Production List |publisher=[[Directors Guild of Canada]] |date=November 30, 2018 |accessdate=December 5, 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6xvXYXENE?url=https://www.dgc.ca/assets/Uploads/BritishColumbia/AvailsProductionLists/Documents/Production-List.pdf |archivedate=March 15, 2018 }}</ref> Filming had been expected to begin in February 2018 and last until June 2018.<ref name=\"THRFilming\" /> The first episode of the second part was the eleventh episode filmed, while the Christmas special was the twelfth episode filmed, despite the Christmas special being released as the eleventh episode overall in the series. This was because the idea for the Christmas special came about when the first episode of the second part was \"too far down the line\" to alter its production schedule. Despite the production switch, Aguirre-Sacasa said the first episode of the second part was written \"as a premiere episode for the second part\" and helps kick-off the storylines for the part.<ref name=\"ChristmasSpecialWrap\" /> Production on the second season, consisting of the third and fourth parts, began on May 17, 2019, and concluded on February 22, 2020.<ref name=\"S2ProductionDates\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dgc.ca/assets/Uploads/BritishColumbia/AvailsProductionLists/Documents/Production-List.pdf |title=DGC BC Production List |publisher=[[Directors Guild of Canada]] |date=February 21, 2020 |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223221302/https://www.dgc.ca/assets/Uploads/BritishColumbia/AvailsProductionLists/Documents/Production-List.pdf |archivedate=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Connection to ''Riverdale''===\nThe series was originally conceived as a companion series to ''Riverdale'' when it was in development for The CW; however, after the series was moved to Netflix, it was unclear if any connection would remain. In January 2018, CW president Mark Pedowitz noted that, \"at the moment, there is no discussion about crossing over.\"<ref name=\"PedowtizJan2018\">{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/01/07/sabrina-riverdale-cw-netflix/|title=Why the Sabrina the Teenage Witch series went to Netflix over the CW|last=Abrams|first=Natalie|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=January 7, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> In March 2018, Jon Goldwater confirmed that the two series were \"two separate entities for right now\" but \"would love it if they could figure out a way to cross over.\" Goldwater also felt there was a possibility for the characters to appear on future episodes of ''Riverdale'', since Greendale had already been mentioned as existing on that series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2018/04/02/riverdale-sabrina-crossover-netflix-the-cw-jon-goldwater/|title=Riverdale EP Shoots Down Talk of a Sabrina Crossover: 'Right Now, We're Not Thinking About That'|last1=Nemetz|first1=Dave|last2=Gelman|first2=Vlada|website=[[TVLine]]|date=April 2, 2018|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSabrina's town, Greendale, is introduced in the second season of ''Riverdale''. Following that, several references to the two cities are made regularly in the two series, visually or with dialogues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popbuzz.com/tv-film/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina/riverdale-references-easter-eggs-crossover/|title=All the Riverdale references and easter eggs in Chilling Adventures of Sabrina|last=Smith|first=Katie Louise|work=PopBuzz|date=October 30, 2018|accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref> In the first season of ''Chilling Adventures of Sabrina'', Moses Thiessen reprises his role as Ben Button from ''Riverdale'' during an episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/riverdale-cameo-chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-ben-button|title=That Riverdale Cameo on Sabrina Has Deep Implications For Both Shows' Mythologies|last=Logan|first=Elizabeth|work=[[W (magazine)|W Magazine]]|date=October 28, 2018|accessdate=October 31, 2018}}</ref> In the episode \"Chapter Sixty-Seven: Varsity Blues\" from the fourth season of ''Riverdale'', [[Ty Wood]] reprises his role as Billy Marlin from ''Sabrina''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/riverdale-cameo-billy-chilling-adventures-sabrina/|title=Riverdale Connects To Chilling Adventures Of Sabrina With [SPOILER] Cameo|last=Behbakht|first=Andy|work=Screen Rant|date=January 23, 2020|accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn episode \"Chapter Twenty-Three: Heavy Is the Crown\" from the third part of ''Sabrina'', the teenage witch and her cousin visit Riverdale in search for a crown that was owned by Benjamin Blossom, an ancestor of [[Cheryl Blossom|Cheryl]]. On their way, they pass the town sign. On its back, [[Jughead Jones]] spray painted the message \"JJ Wuz Here\", his signature. Three episodes later, a member of the Southside Serpents is attacked by Hilda Spellman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/01/24/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-part-3-riverdale-easter-eggs/|title=All the Riverdale Easter eggs in Chilling Adventures of Sabrina Part 3|last=Romano|first=Nick|work=Entertainement Weekly|date=January 24, 2020|accessdate=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRegarding a proper crossover, Aguirre-Sacasa said in October 2018 he would \"hate [for a crossover] to never happen\" between the two series, adding that a potential idea for one would see the characters of ''Riverdale'' \"hear[ing] about a haunted house in Greendale and try[ing] to break in and it's Sabrina's house\". He also stated that since both series were already established, a crossover could happen in a standalone film with both casts, potentially titled ''Afterlife with Archie'', based on the [[Archie Horror]] comic book series of the [[Afterlife with Archie|same name]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/10/26/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-riverdale-crossover-2/|title=Chilling Adventures of Sabrina boss has a few ideas for a Riverdale crossover|last=Highfill|first=Samantha|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=October 26, 2018|accessdate=November 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Lawsuit===\nIn November 2018, [[Satanic Temple]] activists sued the series' production team over the use of the statue of [[Baphomet]], which they claim was a direct copy of their own statue and portrayed the Temple in an inaccurate and derogatory way.<ref>{{cite tweet|author=Lucien Greaves|user=LucienGreaves|number=1057418640243466242|date=October 30, 2018|title=For purposes of comparison...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/biz/news/netflix-satanic-temple-1203023245|title=Satanic Temple Sues Netflix Over \u2018Chilling Adventures of Sabrina\u2019|last=Maddeus|first=Gene|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=November 8, 2018|accessdate=November 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/amp/world-us-canada-46147144|title=Sabrina makers sued by Satanic Temple over statue|work=[[BBC News]]|date=November 9, 2018}}</ref> On November 21, 2018, it was confirmed that Satanic Temple and Netflix have amicably settled the lawsuit dispute, with the terms of the deal left undisclosed to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-satanic-temple-lawsuit-20181121-story.html|title=Satanic Temple's lawsuit over Netflix's 'Chilling Adventures of Sabrina' is settled|last=Lee|first=Wendy|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 21, 2018|accessdate=December 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nOn March 15, 2019, [[WaterTower Music]] released a digital [[Extended play|EP]] with four songs performed by some of the members of the series' cast during the first part of the first season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/chilling-adventures-sabrina-season-1-selections-from/1456325157|title=Chilling Adventures of Sabrina: Season 1 (Selections from the Netflix Series) \u2013 EP|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=March 15, 2019|accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> A compilation of songs from the first season, including six songs performed by the cast (four from the EP and two new songs), was released on digital by WaterTower Music on April 5, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Soundtrack-for-Season-One-of-CHILLING-ADVENTURES-OF-SABRINA-is-Available-Now-20190405|title=Soundtrack for Season One of Chilling Adventures of Sabrina is Available Now|publisher=Broadway World|date=April 5, 2019|accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> Soundtrack from the first part of the second season was released on January 24, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/570wUfq3oTe6g68e6HgBBb|title=Chilling Adventures of Sabrina \u2013 Part 3 Soundtrack|publisher=Spotify|date=January 24, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn album of [[Adam Taylor]]'s scoring for season 1 was released on compact disc by La-La Land Records, and simultaneously on download by WaterTower Music, on August 16, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lalalandrecords.com/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-original-television-score-season-one-limited-edition/|title=Chilling Adventures of Sabrina \u2013 Original Television Score \u2013 Season One|publisher=La-La Land Records|date=January 24, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> A vinyl edition including the soundtrack and the score from the first season was also be released by Waxwork Records in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://waxworkrecords.com/blogs/news/chilling-adventures-of-sabrina-3xlp|title=Chilling Adventures Of Sabrina 3xLP!|publisher=Waxwork Records|date=January 24, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Season 1===\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed    = yes\n| headline     = ''Chilling Adventures of Sabrina: Original Television Soundtrack \u2013 Season One''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/chilling-adventures-sabrina-season-1-original-television/1458638596?app=itunes&ign-mpt=uo%3D4|title=Chilling Adventures of Sabrina: Season 1 (Original Television Soundtrack)|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=April 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| extra_column = Artist(s)\n\n| title1   = Main Title (Chilling Adventures of Sabrina)\n| extra1   = [[Adam Taylor]]\n| length1  = 1:39\n| title2   = [[Bad Moon Rising]]\n| extra2   = [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]]\n| length2  = 2:21\n| title3   = [[I Put a Spell on You]]\n| extra3   = Sylvia Black\n| length3  = 2:40\n| title4   = Terrible Thing\n| extra4   = AG\n| length4  = 3:38\n| title5   = [[16 Candles (song)|Sixteen Candles]]\n| extra5   = [[Stray Cats]]\n| length5  = 2:54\n| title6   = New Kind Of Kick\n| extra6   = [[The Cramps]]\n| length6  = 3:29