s |first=Patrick |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=May 15, 2019 |accessdate=May 15, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515054618/https://deadline.com/2019/05/mtv-movie-tv-awards-2019-nominees-nominations-full-list-1202614793/ |archivedate=May 15, 2019 |url-status=live |df=}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[45th Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]]\n| Best Streaming Horror & Thriller Series \n| ''Chilling Adventures of Sabrina''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mancuso |first1=Vinnie |title='Avengers: Endgame', 'Game of Thrones' Lead the 2019 Saturn Awards Nominations |url=http://collider.com/saturn-awards-nominations-2019/ |website=Collider |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Actress in a Streaming Presentation\n| Kiernan Shipka\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[2019 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Sci-Fi/Fantasy TV Show\n| ''Chilling Adventures of Sabrina''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=3|<ref>{{cite web |title=Lil Nas X & Post Malone Lead 2019 Teen Choice Awards Nominations: See the List |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8516707/2019-teen-choice-awards-nominations |website=Billboard |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice Sci-Fi/Fantasy TV Actor\n| Ross Lynch\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Choice Sci-Fi/Fantasy TV Actress\n| Kiernan Shipka\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|7569592}}\n\n{{Sabrina, the Teenage Witch}}\n{{Archie Comics IOM}}\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n{{Portal bar|Society|Television|United States}}\n[[Category:2010s American LGBT-related drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American high school television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American horror television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American supernatural television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American teen drama television series]]\n[[Category:2018 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related web series]]\n[[Category:Angels in television]]\n[[Category:Astral projection in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Demons in television]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Horror drama television series]]\n[[Category:Horror fiction web series]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Neopaganism in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Sabrina the Teenage Witch]]\n[[Category:Satanism in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Television about magic]]\n[[Category:Television programs about spirit possession]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on Archie Comics]]\n[[Category:Television series by Warner Bros. Television]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in the United States]]\n[[Category:The Devil in fiction]]\n[[Category:Transgender-related television programs]]\n[[Category:Voodoo in fiction]]\n[[Category:Witchcraft in television]]\n", "name_user": "James2354", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chilling_Adventures_of_Sabrina_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Dolittle (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 film directed by Stephen Gaghan}} \n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dolittle\n| image          = Dolittle (2020 film poster).png\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Stephen Gaghan]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Joe Roth]]\n* Jeff Kirschenbaum\n* [[Susan Downey]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Stephen Gaghan\n* Dan Gregor\n* Doug Mand\n}}\n| story          = Thomas Shepherd\n| based on       = {{based on|[[Doctor Dolittle]]||[[Hugh Lofting]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Downey Jr.]]\n* [[Antonio Banderas]]\n* [[Michael Sheen]]\n* [[Emma Thompson]]\n* [[Rami Malek]]\n* [[John Cena]]\n* [[Kumail Nanjiani]]\n* [[Octavia Spencer]]\n* [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]]\n* [[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]]\n* [[Ralph Fiennes]]\n* [[Selena Gomez]]\n* [[Marion Cotillard]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Danny Elfman]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/07/16/danny-elfman-to-score-the-voyage-of-doctor-dolittle/ |title=Danny Elfman to Score 'The Voyage of Doctor Dolittle' |website=Film Music Reporter |access-date=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n| cinematography = [[Guillermo Navarro]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Craig Alpert]]\n* [[Nick Moore (film director)|Nick Moore]]\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Roth/Kirschenbaum Films\n* [[Team Downey]]\n* [[Perfect World Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|1|17|United States}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $175 million<ref name=reshoots/>\n| gross          = $227.9 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2164295169/?ref_=bo_tt_gr_1 |title=Dolittle (2020) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NUM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Dolittle#tab=summary |title=Dolittle (2020) |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Dolittle''''' (also referred to as '''''The Voyage of Doctor Dolittle''''') is a 2020 American [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[comedy film|comedy]] [[adventure film]] directed by [[Stephen Gaghan]] from a screenplay by Gaghan, Dan Gregor, and Doug Mand, based on a story by Thomas Shepherd. A reboot of the [[Doctor Dolittle (1967 film)|original ''Doctor Dolittle'' film]] and its [[Dr. Dolittle (1998 film)|modern comedy counterparts]], the film is based on the [[Doctor Dolittle|titular character]] created by [[Hugh Lofting]], and primarily inspired by ''[[The Voyages of Doctor Dolittle]]'', the author's second Doctor Dolittle book. [[Robert Downey Jr.]] stars as the title character, alongside [[Antonio Banderas]] and [[Michael Sheen]] in live action roles, and a voice cast including [[Emma Thompson]], [[Rami Malek]], [[John Cena]], [[Kumail Nanjiani]], [[Octavia Spencer]], [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]], [[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]], [[Ralph Fiennes]], [[Selena Gomez]], and [[Marion Cotillard]]. \n\nThe project was announced in March 2017 with Downey set to star, and the rest of the cast joined over the following year. Filming began in March 2018 and lasted through June, taking place around the United Kingdom. The film underwent three weeks of reshoots in the spring of 2019, under the supervision of [[Jonathan Liebesman]] and [[Chris McKay]], after initial test screenings yielded poor results.\n\n''Dolittle'' was theatrically released in the United States on January 17, 2020, by [[Universal Pictures]]. It received generally negative reviews from critics for its screenplay, plot and humor. Having grossed $223 million worldwide against its $175 million budget, it is the [[2020 in film|third highest-grossing film of 2020]], although it was a [[box office bomb]], with projected losses for the studio as high as $100 million.\n\n==Plot==\nIn early [[Victorian era]] [[England]], Dr. John Dolittle ([[Robert Downey Jr.]]) is a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] [[veterinarian]] who has the ability to communicate with animals. After his wife, Lily ([[Kasia Smutniak]]) dies at sea, Dolittle becomes a recluse, tending to only animals and refusing to contact or assist with other humans. One day, a boy named Tommy Stubbins ([[Harry Collett]]) accidentally shoots and wounds a [[squirrel]] named Kevin ([[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]]) and is guided to Dolittle for help by a [[blue and gold macaw]] named Polynesia, (Poly for short) ([[Emma Thompson]]). \n\nMeanwhile, [[Queen Victoria]] ([[Jessie Buckley]]) sends a girl named Lady Rose ([[Carmel Laniado]]) with a message, ordering Dolittle to come in order to try to cure the queen of a deadly sickness. After being persuaded by Poly that he has to start trying to reconnect with fellow humans, Dolittle finally decides to go. Upon reaching her, he finds that the Queen has been poisoned by a type of [[Solanaceae|nightshade]] that was added to her [[tea]]. To be cured, she must eat a fruit from a far away land.\n\nAfter Poly, Betsy the [[giraffe]] ([[Selena Gomez]]) and Tutu the [[fox]] ([[Marion Cotillard]]) help Tommy escape from his home, he, Dolittle, and Dolittle's crew of animals, consisting of Poly, Kevin, [[Capuchin|capuchin]]s Elliot and Elsie, Chee-Chee the [[gorilla]] ([[Rami Malek]]), Yoshi the [[polar bear]] ([[John Cena]]), Plimpton the [[ostrich]] ([[Kumail Nanjiani]]), Dab-Dab the [[duck]] ([[Octavia Spencer]]) and Mini the [[sugar glider]] (Nick A. Fisher) put to sail, hoping to find the cure while trying to escape Dolittle's lifelong rival Dr. Blair M\u00fcdfly ([[Michael Sheen]]). Dolittle leaves his [[lurcher]] Jip ([[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]]) and a [[Phasmatodea|walking stick]] behind to guard the Queen while he's traveling. Along the way, Dolittle's boat is attacked by M\u00fcdfly, but they manage to escape by attaching a harness to a [[humpback whale]] that pulls the boat to safety.\n\nThey continue to the island where Lily was born. While attempting to steal Lily's journal which details the way to the fruit tree, Dolittle is captured by his former father-in-law King Rassouli ([[Antonio Banderas]]) and is locked in a cage with Barry ([[Ralph Fiennes]]), a moody [[tiger]] looking for his mother's approval. Just when it seems Dolittle is to be killed, Chee-Chee arrives and incapacitates Barry. Dolittle and Tommy escape only to be captured by M\u00fcdfly and have their ship destroyed. After seeing a crestfallen Dolittle, Rassouli loans him a boat to honour his daughter.\n\nTrailing M\u00fcdfly, Dolittle and company arrive at the cure tree's island, where they meet Ginko-Who-Soars ([[Frances de la Tour]]), a [[dragon]] who guards the tree since her husband's death. Ginko begins attacking (even accidentally make M\u00fcdfly fall into a hole) before she collapses due to internal pain. Dolittle figures out what is hurting the dragon and proceeds to remove [[armour]] and [[bagpipes]] causing a blockage in her stomach. Relieved and thankful, Ginko shows Dolittle the tree with the cure.\n\nDolittle's entourage returns just in time to heal the queen. Dolittle\u2019s walking stick reveals that Lord Thomas Badgley ([[Jim Broadbent]]), one of the Queen's chairmen, poisoned her in order to take the crown for himself, and was the one who sent M\u00fcdfly to fail Dolittle's quest. The Queen has sent to the [[Tower of London|Tower]] for treason, and thanks Dolittle for saving her.\n\nDolittle re-opens the doors to his sanctuary, now including Tommy as his apprentice.\n\nIn a mid-credits scene, M\u00fcdfly, who had survive his fall, is trying to talk with the [[bats]] who turn around and attack him.\n\n==Cast==\n{{seealso|List of Doctor Dolittle characters}}\n* [[Robert Downey Jr.]] as [[Doctor Dolittle|Dr. John Dolittle]], a widowed veterinarian who has the ability to speak to animals.\n* [[Harry Collett]] as Tommy Stubbins, a plucky and kind boy who becomes Dolittle's self-appointed apprentice.\n* [[Antonio Banderas]] as King Rassouli, the king of [[pirate]]s who was Lily's father and Dolittle\u2019s father-in-law.\n* [[Michael Sheen]] as Dr. Blair M\u00fcdfly, an old schoolmate and rival of Dolittle who gradually becomes impressed by Dolittle's special ability.\n* [[Jim Broadbent]] as Lord Thomas Badgley, one of the Queen's treacherous chairmen.\n* [[Jessie Buckley]] as [[Queen Victoria]], the Queen of England.\n* [[Carmel Laniado]] as Lady Rose, a maid of honor to the Queen and Tommy's friend and love interest.\n* [[Kasia Smutniak]] as Lily Dolittle, a virtuous explorer who was Dolittle's deceased wife and King Rassouli's daughter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.it/show/cinema/2018/06/18/kasia-smutniak-sul-set-con-robert-downey-jr |title=Kasia Smutniak: \"Sul set con Robert Downey Jr.\" |date=2018-06-18 |website=VanityFair.it |language=it |access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref> \n* [[Ralph Ineson]] as Arnall Stubbins, Tommy's uncle.\n* [[Joanna Page]] as Bethan Stubbins, Tommy's aunt.\n* Sonny Ashbourne Serkis as Arnall Stubbins Jr., Tommy's cousin.\n* Elliot Barnes-Worrell as Captain William Derrick, a British Captain Officer who follows Dr. M\u00fcdfly\u2019s orders.\n\n===Voices===\n* [[Emma Thompson]] as Polynesia, (Poly for short), a wise and brave [[blue and gold macaw|macaw]] and Dolittle\u2019s most trusted advisor.\n* [[Rami Malek]] as Chee-Chee, a nervous but noble [[gorilla]].\n* [[John Cena]] as Yoshi, a happy-go-lucky but always cold [[polar bear]] who wears a [[chullo]].\n* [[Kumail Nanjiani]] as Plimpton, a fussy and reluctant but well-meaning [[ostrich]] who wears striped [[stockings]] and quarrels with Yoshi.\n* [[Octavia Spencer]] as Dab-Dab, a helpful but deluded [[duck]] with a metal leg.\n* [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]] as Jip, a loyal [[lurcher]] who wears glasses.\n* [[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]] as Kevin, a cheeky-chappy [[squirrel]] with attitude.\n* [[Ralph Fiennes]] as Barry, an aggressive [[tiger]] who has a past with Dolittle and wants to please his mother.\n* [[Selena Gomez]] as Betsy, a friendly [[giraffe]].\n* [[Marion Cotillard]] as Tutu, a French [[fox]] who is best friends with Betsy.\n* [[Jason Mantzoukas]] as James, a comical [[dragonfly]] who meets Dolittle in a prison cell from which he helps him escape.\n* [[Frances de la Tour]] as Ginko-Who-Soars, a fire-breathing [[dragon]] who guards the magical fruits of Eden.\n* Nick A. Fisher as Mini, a cute sugar glider.\n* Tim Trelor as Humphrey, a [[humpback whale]].\n* Jim Carretta as Beard Mouse\n** Jim Carretta also voices Leona\n* Ranjani Brow and [[Kelly Stables]] as Mice\n* [[Scott Menville]] as Army Ant\n* [[Will Arnett]] as a rabbit in one of Rassouli's prison cells and a friend of Barry.\n\nBaby animals voiced by Gia Davis, Henry Holcomb, Kyrie Mcalpin, and Isley Zamora.\n\n==Production==\nOn March 20, 2017, it was announced that [[Robert Downey Jr.]] would star in ''The Voyage of Doctor Dolittle'', a feature adaptation of ''[[The Voyages of Doctor Dolittle]].''<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/robert-downey-jr-star-voyage-doctor-dolittle-986798 |title=Robert Downey Jr. to Star in 'The Voyage of Doctor Dolittle' |date=March 20, 2017 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=March 21, 2017 |last2=Kit |first2=Borys |language=en}}</ref> In December 2017, Harry Collett and [[Jim Broadbent]] were cast.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/robert-downey-jr-doctor-dolittle-movie-harry-collett-1202632151/ |title=Robert Downey Jr.'s 'Voyage of Doctor Dolittle' Taps 'Dunkirk' Actor Harry Collett (EXCLUSIVE) |last=Kroll |first=Justin |last2=Kroll |first2=Justin |date=6 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kroll |first=Justin |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/jim-broadbent-voyage-of-doctor-dolittle-robert-downey-jr-1202638025/ |title=Jim Broadbent Joins Robert Downey Jr. in Universal's 'Voyage of Doctor Dolittle' (EXCLUSIVE) |date=2017-12-12 |work=Variety |access-date=2018-03-27 |language=en-US}}</ref> In February 2018, [[Antonio Banderas]] and [[Michael Sheen]] were cast in live-action roles, while [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]], [[Emma Thompson]], [[Ralph Fiennes]], and [[Selena Gomez]] were cast to voice animals, including a tiger, bear, and a lioness.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tom-holland-emma-thompson-join-robert-downey-jr-doctor-dolittle-1081903 |title=Tom Holland, Emma Thompson Join Robert Downey Jr. in 'Doctor Dolittle' |website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref name=\"Galuppo\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/doctor-dolittle-movie-selena-gomez-joins-robert-downey-jr-1081896 |title=Selena Gomez Joins Robert Downey Jr.'s 'Doctor Dolittle' Movie (Exclusive) |last=Galuppo |first=Mia |website=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en |access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> In March 2018, [[Kumail Nanjiani]], [[Octavia Spencer]], [[John Cena]], [[Rami Malek]], [[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]], [[Marion Cotillard]], [[Frances de la Tour]] and [[Carmen Ejogo]] joined the voice cast.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/voyage-doctor-dolittle-cast-robert-downey-jr-unveils-full-list-1097797 |title=Robert Downey Jr. Unveils Voice Cast for 'Voyage of Doctor Dolittle' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=2018-03-27 |language=en}}</ref> The character of Regine, a lioness voiced by Ejogo, was cut from the finished film.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nPrincipal production commenced mid-February in 2018. Live-action scenes began filming in [[Kirkby Lonsdale]], [[Cumbria]] in May 2018, with further location filming at South Forest, [[Windsor Great Park]] and on the [[Menai Suspension Bridge]] in [[North West Wales]], in June 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-44391624 |title=Hollywood film crew fixes giant pothole |date=2018-06-07 |work=BBC News |access-date=2018-06-12 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, it was reported the film had undergone 21 days of [[Pick-up (filmmaking)|re-shoots]] following poor test screenings. Director [[Jonathan Liebesman]] helped to oversee the filming alongside [[Stephen Gaghan|Gaghan]], while [[Chris McKay]] helped write new material after it became clear from first cuts that the comedy elements of the film were not coming together as well as the producers had hoped.<ref name=\"reshoots\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/ninja-turtles-director-tackling-doctor-dolittle-reshoots-1201707 |title='Ninja Turtles' Director Jonathan Liebesman Tackling 'Doctor Dolittle' Reshoots (Exclusive) |last=Borys Kit |date=April 15, 2019 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=April 15, 2019}}</ref> Prior to this, Universal had turned towards [[Seth Rogen]] and ''[[Neighbors (2014 film)|Neighbors]]'' co-writer [[Brendan O'Brien (screenwriter)|Brendan O'Brien]] to help make the film funnier. However, neither could remain committed to the project and dropped out. McKay was assigned to storyboard sequences and assemble different edits before later leaving to instead direct ''[[The Tomorrow War]]''. Liebesman took over McKay's duties and finished the film alongside Gaghan. ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'' scribe John Whittington had performed rewrites on the script amid reshoots and had flown to [[London]] to meet with Downey, who allegedly tore Whittington's script apart in favor of \"new ideas\". ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' claims that despite a \"challenged production\" there were no fights for power and no competing cuts for the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/behind-robert-downey-jrs-dolittle-debacle-1272759 |title=\"I Have Some New Ideas\": The Scramble Behind Robert Downey Jr.'s ''Dolittle'' Debacle |last=Kit |first=Borys |last2=McClintock |first2=Pamela |date=January 31, 2020 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> In August 2019, it was reported that the film's title had been changed from ''The Voyage of Doctor Dolittle'' to simply ''Dolittle''.<ref name=\"VT\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vitalthrills.com/2019/08/12/dolittle-synopsis-new-title-january-release/ |title=Dolittle Synopsis and New Title for the January Release |last=Parlevliet |first=Mirko |date=2019-08-12 |website=VitalThrills.com |language=en-US |access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, [[Robert Downey Jr]] discussed on [[Joe Rogan]]'s podcast (''The Joe Rogan Experience'') that the premise of the Dr. Dolittle character in his film stemmed from a [[Culture of Wales|Welsh]] neo-pagan physician called [[William Price (physician)|William Price]]. In the podcast he said: \n\"Same way I did with Iron Man.. all right there's something here and then before I signed on, I was just googling 'weirdest Welsh doctor', I just wanted to think of, I don't want to just do another English accent.. so there was this guy called William Price, who's a nutty Welsh doctor, he was a neo-druidist, he believed that he could communicate with all nature and all that stuff, so I sent a picture of this wild looking guy wearing this kind of suit with stars on it and like a staff in his hand, so I sent that to Gaghan and he goes, \"That looks good to me\" and I was like \"great let's do this movie\"\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d5XTDmm0KUQ |title=Joe Rogan Experience #1411 - Robert Downey Jr. |date=2020-01-15 |publisher=YouTube |access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nMusic artist [[Sia (musician)|Sia]] performed a new song of hers called \"[[Original (Sia song)|Original]]\" for the end credits, while Danny Elfman composed the film's score.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZBEUQjt1-iE |title=Sia - Original (from Dolittle Soundtrack) |date=2020-01-09 |publisher=YouTube |access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was originally going to be released on May 24, 2019, by [[Universal Pictures]] but was moved to April 12, 2019, to avoid competition with ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker]]'' (which was later moved to December 20, 2019). The film was later moved again to January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/doctor-dolittle-movie-delayed-2020/|title=Robert Downey Jr's Doctor Dolittle Movie Delayed to January 2020|date=October 1, 2018|work=Screen Rant}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Dolittle'' was released on [[Digital HD]] on March 24, 2020 and was released on [[DVD]], [[Blu-ray]], and [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]] on April 7, 2020. <ref name=\"DVDsReleaseDates\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/8968/dolittle |title=Dolittle DVD Release Date |website=DVDs Release Dates |language=en |access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2020|3|19|df=US}}, ''Dolittle'' has grossed $77 million in the United States and Canada, and $146.3 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $227.9 million, against a production budget of $175 million.<ref name=\"BOM\" /><ref name=\"NUM\" /> Due to its high production and marketing costs, the film will need to gross around $500 million in order to [[break even]];<ref>{{Cite news |last=Katz |first=Brandon |url=https://observer.com/2019/12/2020-movie-release-schedule-box-office-bombs-prediction/ |title=Which Movies Are Most Likely to Bomb in 2020? |date=December 31, 2019 |work=[[The New York Observer]] |access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> following its debut weekend, it was estimated the film would lose the studio between $50\u2013100 million.<ref name=opening/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/robert-downey-jrs-dolittle-could-lose-100-million-at-box-office/ |title=Robert Downey Jr's 'Dolittle' Could Lose $100 Million at Box Office |last=Jeremy Fuster |date=January 19, 2020 |website=[[TheWrap]] |access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was projected to gross $20\u201322 million from 4,155 theaters in its opening weekend, and a total of around $27 million over the four-day [[Martin Luther King Jr. Day]] weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/01/bad-boys-for-life-dolittle-will-smith-robert-downey-jr-1917-oscar-nominations-box-office-1202831808/ |title=Can 'Bad Boys For Life' Keep The Sony Franchise Alive? \u2013 Box Office Preview\n|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author= Anthony D'Alessandro |accessdate=January 15, 2020|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/can-bad-boys-for-life-succeed-for-sony-where-mib-international-failed/ |title=Can 'Bad Boys for Life' Succeed for Sony Where 'MIB: International' Failed? |last=Jeremy Fuster |date=January 14, 2020 |publisher=[[TheWrap]] |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> It made $6.3 million on its first day, including $925,000 from Thursday night previews. It went on to debut to $22 million (and $29.5 million over the four-day frame), finishing third behind fellow newcomer ''[[Bad Boys for Life]]'' and holdover ''[[1917 (2019 film)|1917]]''.<ref name=\"opening\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/bad-boys-for-life-dolittle-1917-weekend-box-office-1202833726/ |title=How Sony Built 'Bad Boys For Life' Into A Success With $101M+ WW & $73M+ U.S.; 'Dolittle' Poised For $50M+ Loss \u2013 Monday Update |last=Anthony D'Alessandro |date=January 21, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=January 20, 2020}}</ref> The film made $12.1 million in its second weekend and $7.7 million in its third, remaining in third both times.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/bad-boys-for-life-the-gentleman-the-turning-weekend-box-office-1202840184/ |title='Bad Boys For Life' & '1917' Shooting Past $100M; 'The Turning' Slammed With Second 'F' Of 2020 |last=Anthony D'Alessandro |date=January 24, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/01/gretel-hansel-finds-475k-the-rhythm-section-offbeat-with-235k-thursday-night-previews-1202847821/ |title='Bad Boys For Life' Scores Over Super Bowl Weekend With $17M+; 'Rhythm Section' Is A Mess\n|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=February 2, 2020|date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film held an approval rating of 15% based on 212 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 3.85/10. The website's critics consensus reads, \"''Dolittle'' may be enough to entertain very young viewers, but they deserve better than this rote adaptation's jumbled story and stale humor.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dolittle/ |title=Dolittle (2020) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film had a weighted average score of 26 out of 100, based on 46 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dolittle |title=Dolittle Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported a viewer average of 3 out of 5 stars.<ref name=opening/>\n\nCourtney Howard of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the film a \"frenetic, crass kids' flick\" and wrote: \"What should have been an awe-filled adventure quickly curdles into an awful one, thanks to a pedestrian formula and the filmmakers' fixation on fart jokes.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/reviews/dolittle-review-1203467269/ |title='Dolittle': Film Review |last=Courtney Howard |date=January 15, 2020 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', [[Todd McCarthy]] said that \"From the very first scene, it's clear something is terribly off with this lavishly misbegotten attempt to repopularize an animal-loaded literary franchise that was born exactly a century ago. The oddly diffident star and executive producer Robert Downey Jr. never finds the power-supplying third rail needed to energize a tale that fails to make a real case for being reinterpreted\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/dolittle-review-1269681 |title='Dolittle': Film Review |last=Todd McCarthy |date=January 15, 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBritish film critic [[Mark Kermode]] gave the film a negative review, saying, \"Terrible script. Terrible visuals. Dull plot. Dismal gags. The fact that at 101 minutes it really tested one's patience. It is shockingly poor.\" He particularly criticized Robert Downey Jr.'s attempt at a Welsh accent, calling it \"something from Mars.\"<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1iEIHsv3jkY |title=Dolittle reviewed by Mark Kermode |date=February 7, 2020 |access-date=2020-02-11 |medium=video |via=YouTube}}</ref> In examining the films ending, Douglas Laman of ''[[Screen Rant]]'' noted that the film as a whole suffered from numerous problems, including \"...Dolittle's new backstory involving a deceased wife...the largely lifeless voice-over work of the animal characters [and] its painfully unfunny comedy.\" <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/dolittle-movie-ending-bad-explained/ |title=Dolittle Movie Ending Explained: Why It's So Bad |last=Douglas Laman |date=March 30, 2020 |website=[[Screen Rant]] |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{Doctor Dolittle}}\n{{Stephen Gaghan}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020 fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s children's adventure films]]\n[[Category:2020s children's fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Doctor Dolittle films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about animals]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Stephen Gaghan]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Danny Elfman]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1819]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Shepperton Studios]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Wales]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Stephen Gaghan]]\n[[Category:Motion capture in film]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 film directed by Stephen Gaghan}} \n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dolittle\n| image          = Dolittle (2020 film poster).png\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Stephen Gaghan]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Joe Roth]]\n* Jeff Kirschenbaum\n* [[Susan Downey]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Stephen Gaghan\n* Dan Gregor\n* Doug Mand\n}}\n| story          = Thomas Shepherd\n| based on       = {{based on|[[Doctor Dolittle]]||[[Hugh Lofting]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Downey Jr.]]\n* [[Antonio Banderas]]\n* [[Michael Sheen]]\n* [[Emma Thompson]]\n* [[Rami Malek]]\n* [[John Cena]]\n* [[Kumail Nanjiani]]\n* [[Octavia Spencer]]\n* [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]]\n* [[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]]\n* [[Ralph Fiennes]]\n* [[Selena Gomez]]\n* [[Marion Cotillard]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Danny Elfman]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/07/16/danny-elfman-to-score-the-voyage-of-doctor-dolittle/ |title=Danny Elfman to Score 'The Voyage of Doctor Dolittle' |website=Film Music Reporter |access-date=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n| cinematography = [[Guillermo Navarro]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Craig Alpert]]\n* [[Nick Moore (film director)|Nick Moore]]\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Roth/Kirschenbaum Films\n* [[Team Downey]]\n* [[Perfect World Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|1|17|United States}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $175 million<ref name=reshoots/>\n| gross          = $227.9 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2164295169/?ref_=bo_tt_gr_1 |title=Dolittle (2020) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NUM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Dolittle#tab=summary |title=Dolittle (2020) |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Dolittle''''' (also referred to as '''''The Voyage of Doctor Dolittle''''') is a 2020 American [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[comedy film|comedy]] [[adventure film]] directed by [[Stephen Gaghan]] from a screenplay by Gaghan, Dan Gregor, and Doug Mand, based on a story by Thomas Shepherd. A reboot of the [[Doctor Dolittle (1967 film)|original ''Doctor Dolittle'' film]] and its [[Dr. Dolittle (1998 film)|modern comedy counterparts]], the film is based on the [[Doctor Dolittle|titular character]] created by [[Hugh Lofting]], and primarily inspired by ''[[The Voyages of Doctor Dolittle]]'', the author's second Doctor Dolittle book. [[Robert Downey Jr.]] stars as the title character, alongside [[Antonio Banderas]] and [[Michael Sheen]] in live action roles, and a voice cast including [[Emma Thompson]], [[Rami Malek]], [[John Cena]], [[Kumail Nanjiani]], [[Octavia Spencer]], [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]], [[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]], [[Ralph Fiennes]], [[Selena Gomez]], and [[Marion Cotillard]]. \n\nThe project was announced in March 2017 with Downey set to star, and the rest of the cast joined over the following year. Filming began in March 2018 and lasted through June, taking place around the United Kingdom. The film underwent three weeks of reshoots in the spring of 2019, under the supervision of [[Jonathan Liebesman]] and [[Chris McKay]], after initial test screenings yielded poor results.\n\n''Dolittle'' was theatrically released in the United States on January 17, 2020, by [[Universal Pictures]]. It received generally negative reviews from critics for its screenplay, plot and humor. Having grossed $223 million worldwide against its $175 million budget, it is the [[2020 in film|third highest-grossing film of 2020]], although it was a [[box office bomb]], with projected losses for the studio as high as $100 million.\n\n==Plot==\nIn early Victorian era England, Dr. John Dolittle ([[Robert Downey Jr.]]) is a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] [[veterinarian]] who has the ability to communicate with animals. After his wife, Lily ([[Kasia Smutniak]]) dies at sea, Dolittle becomes a recluse, tending to only animals and refusing to contact or assist with other humans. One day, a boy named Tommy Stubbins ([[Harry Collett]]) accidentally shoots and wounds a squirrel named Kevin ([[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]]) and is guided to Dolittle for help by a macaw named Polynesia, (Poly for short) ([[Emma Thompson]]). \n\nMeanwhile, [[Queen Victoria]] ([[Jessie Buckley]]) sends a girl named Lady Rose ([[Carmel Laniado]]) with a message, ordering Dolittle to come in order to try to cure the queen of a deadly sickness. After being persuaded by Poly that he has to start trying to reconnect with fellow humans, Dolittle finally decides to go. Upon reaching her, he finds that the Queen has been poisoned by a type of [[Solanaceae|nightshade]] that was added to her tea. To be cured, she must eat a fruit from a far away land.\n\nAfter Poly, Betsy the giraffe ([[Selena Gomez]]) and Tutu the fox ([[Marion Cotillard]]) help Tommy escape from his home, he, Dolittle, and Dolittle's crew of animals, consisting of Poly, Kevin, monkeys Elliot and Elsie, Chee-Chee the gorilla ([[Rami Malek]]), Yoshi the polar bear ([[John Cena]]), Plimpton the ostrich ([[Kumail Nanjiani]]), Dab-Dab the duck ([[Octavia Spencer]]) and Mini the [[sugar glider]] (Nick A. Fisher) put to sail, hoping to find the cure while trying to escape Dolittle's lifelong rival Dr. Blair M\u00fcdfly ([[Michael Sheen]]). Dolittle leaves his [[lurcher]] Jip ([[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]]) and a [[Phasmatodea|walking stick]] behind to guard the Queen while he's traveling. Along the way, Dolittle's boat is attacked by M\u00fcdfly, but they manage to escape by attaching a harness to a whale that pulls the boat to safety.\n\nThey continue to the island where Lily was born. While attempting to steal Lily's journal which details the way to the fruit tree, Dolittle is captured by his former father-in-law King Rassouli ([[Antonio Banderas]]) and is locked in a cage with Barry ([[Ralph Fiennes]]), a moody tiger looking for his mother's approval. Just when it seems Dolittle is to be killed, a now-couragous Chee-Chee arrives and incapacitates Barry. Dolittle and Tommy escape only to be captured by M\u00fcdfly and have their ship destroyed. After seeing a crestfallen Dolittle, Rassouli loans him a boat to honour his daughter.\n\nTrailing M\u00fcdfly, Dolittle and company arrive at the cure tree's island, where they meet Ginko-Who-Soars ([[Frances de la Tour]]), a dragon who guards the tree since her husband's death. Ginko begins attacking (even accidentally make M\u00fcdfly fall into a hole) before she collapses due to internal pain. Dolittle figures out what is hurting the dragon and proceeds to perform a dragon [[enema]]. Relieved and thankful, Ginko shows Dolittle the tree with the cure.\n\nDolittle's entourage returns just in time to heal the queen. Dolittle\u2019s walking stick reveals that Lord Thomas Badgley ([[Jim Broadbent]]), one of the Queen's chairmen, poisoned her in order to take the crown for himself, and was the one who order M\u00fcdfly to fail Dolittle's quest. The Queen has him arrested for treason, and thanks Dolittle for saving her.\n\nDolittle re-opens the doors to his sanctuary, now including Tommy as his official apprentice.\n\nIn a mid-credits scene, M\u00fcdfly, who had survive his fall, is trying to talk with the bats who turn around and attack him.\n\n==Cast==\n{{seealso|List of Doctor Dolittle characters}}\n* [[Robert Downey Jr.]] as [[Doctor Dolittle|Dr. John Dolittle]], a widowed veterinarian who has the ability to speak to animals.\n* [[Harry Collett]] as Tommy Stubbins, Dolittle's self-appointed apprentice.\n* [[Antonio Banderas]] as King Rassouli, the king of pirates who was Lily's father and Dolittle\u2019s father-in-law.\n* [[Michael Sheen]] as Dr. Blair M\u00fcdfly, an old schoolmate and rival of Dolittle who gradually becomes impressed by Dolittle's special ability.\n* [[Jim Broadbent]] as Lord Thomas Badgley, one of the Queen's dishonest chairmen.\n* [[Jessie Buckley]] as [[Queen Victoria]], the Queen of England.\n* [[Carmel Laniado]] as Lady Rose, a maid of honor to the Queen and Tommy's friend and love interest.\n* [[Kasia Smutniak]] as Lily Dolittle, Dolittle's deceased wife and King Rassouli's daughter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.it/show/cinema/2018/06/18/kasia-smutniak-sul-set-con-robert-downey-jr |title=Kasia Smutniak: \"Sul set con Robert Downey Jr.\" |date=2018-06-18 |website=VanityFair.it |language=it |access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref> \n* [[Ralph Ineson]] as Arnall Stubbins, Tommy's uncle.\n* [[Joanna Page]] as Bethan Stubbins, Tommy's aunt.\n* Sonny Ashbourne Serkis as Arnall Stubbins Jr., Tommy's cousin.\n* Elliot Barnes-Worrell as Captain William Derrick, a British Captain Officer who follows Dr. M\u00fcdfly\u2019s orders.\n\n===Voices===\n* [[Emma Thompson]] as Polynesia, (Poly for short), a wise and brave macaw and Dolittle\u2019s most trusted advisor.\n* [[Rami Malek]] as Chee-Chee, a shy but noble gorilla.\n* [[John Cena]] as Yoshi, a happy-go-lucky but always cold polar bear who wears a [[chullo]].\n* [[Kumail Nanjiani]] as Plimpton, a mischievous and critical but well-meaning ostrich who wears striped stockings and quarrels with Yoshi.\n* [[Octavia Spencer]] as Dab-Dab, a helpful but deluded duck with a metal leg.\n* [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]] as Jip, a loyal dog who wears glasses.\n* [[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]] as Kevin, a cheeky-chappy squirrel with attitude.\n* [[Ralph Fiennes]] as Barry, an aggressive tiger who has a past with Dolittle and wants to please his mother.\n* [[Selena Gomez]] as Betsy, a friendly giraffe.\n* [[Marion Cotillard]] as Tutu, a French fox who is best friends with Betsy.\n* [[Jason Mantzoukas]] as James, a comical dragonfly who meets Dolittle in a prison cell from which he helps him escape.\n* [[Frances de la Tour]] as Ginko-Who-Soars, a fire-breathing dragon who guards the magical fruits of Eden.\n* Nick A. Fisher as Mini, a cute sugar glider.\n* Tim Trelor as Humphrey, a whale.\n* Jim Carretta as Beard Mouse\n** Jim Carretta also voices Leona\n* Ranjani Brow and [[Kelly Stables]] as Mice\n* [[Scott Menville]] as Army Ant\n* [[Will Arnett]] as a rabbit in one of Rassouli's prison cells and a friend of Barry.\n\nBaby animals voiced by Gia Davis, Henry Holcomb, Kyrie Mcalpin, and Isley Zamora.\n\n==Production==\nOn March 20, 2017, it was announced that [[Robert Downey Jr.]] would star in ''The Voyage of Doctor Dolittle'', a feature adaptation of ''[[The Voyages of Doctor Dolittle]].''<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/robert-downey-jr-star-voyage-doctor-dolittle-986798 |title=Robert Downey Jr. to Star in 'The Voyage of Doctor Dolittle' |date=March 20, 2017 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=March 21, 2017 |last2=Kit |first2=Borys |language=en}}</ref> In December 2017, Harry Collett and [[Jim Broadbent]] were cast.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/robert-downey-jr-doctor-dolittle-movie-harry-collett-1202632151/ |title=Robert Downey Jr.'s 'Voyage of Doctor Dolittle' Taps 'Dunkirk' Actor Harry Collett (EXCLUSIVE) |last=Kroll |first=Justin |last2=Kroll |first2=Justin |date=6 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kroll |first=Justin |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/jim-broadbent-voyage-of-doctor-dolittle-robert-downey-jr-1202638025/ |title=Jim Broadbent Joins Robert Downey Jr. in Universal's 'Voyage of Doctor Dolittle' (EXCLUSIVE) |date=2017-12-12 |work=Variety |access-date=2018-03-27 |language=en-US}}</ref> In February 2018, [[Antonio Banderas]] and [[Michael Sheen]] were cast in live-action roles, while [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]], [[Emma Thompson]], [[Ralph Fiennes]], and [[Selena Gomez]] were cast to voice animals, including a tiger, bear, and a lioness.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tom-holland-emma-thompson-join-robert-downey-jr-doctor-dolittle-1081903 |title=Tom Holland, Emma Thompson Join Robert Downey Jr. in 'Doctor Dolittle' |website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref name=\"Galuppo\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/doctor-dolittle-movie-selena-gomez-joins-robert-downey-jr-1081896 |title=Selena Gomez Joins Robert Downey Jr.'s 'Doctor Dolittle' Movie (Exclusive) |last=Galuppo |first=Mia |website=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en |access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> In March 2018, [[Kumail Nanjiani]], [[Octavia Spencer]], [[John Cena]], [[Rami Malek]], [[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]], [[Marion Cotillard]], [[Frances de la Tour]] and [[Carmen Ejogo]] joined the voice cast.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/voyage-doctor-dolittle-cast-robert-downey-jr-unveils-full-list-1097797 |title=Robert Downey Jr. Unveils Voice Cast for 'Voyage of Doctor Dolittle' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=2018-03-27 |language=en}}</ref> The character of Regine, a lioness voiced by Ejogo, was cut from the finished film.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nPrincipal production commenced mid-February in 2018. Live-action scenes began filming in [[Kirkby Lonsdale]], [[Cumbria]] in May 2018, with further location filming at South Forest, [[Windsor Great Park]] and on the [[Menai Suspension Bridge]] in [[North West Wales]], in June 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-44391624 |title=Hollywood film crew fixes giant pothole |date=2018-06-07 |work=BBC News |access-date=2018-06-12 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, it was reported the film had undergone 21 days of [[Pick-up (filmmaking)|re-shoots]] following poor test screenings. Director [[Jonathan Liebesman]] helped to oversee the filming alongside [[Stephen Gaghan|Gaghan]], while [[Chris McKay]] helped write new material after it became clear from first cuts that the comedy elements of the film were not coming together as well as the producers had hoped.<ref name=\"reshoots\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/ninja-turtles-director-tackling-doctor-dolittle-reshoots-1201707 |title='Ninja Turtles' Director Jonathan Liebesman Tackling 'Doctor Dolittle' Reshoots (Exclusive) |last=Borys Kit |date=April 15, 2019 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=April 15, 2019}}</ref> Prior to this, Universal had turned towards [[Seth Rogen]] and ''[[Neighbors (2014 film)|Neighbors]]'' co-writer [[Brendan O'Brien (screenwriter)|Brendan O'Brien]] to help make the film funnier. However, neither could remain committed to the project and dropped out. McKay was assigned to storyboard sequences and assemble different edits before later leaving to instead direct ''[[The Tomorrow War]]''. Liebesman took over McKay's duties and finished the film alongside Gaghan. ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'' scribe John Whittington had performed rewrites on the script amid reshoots and had flown to [[London]] to meet with Downey, who allegedly tore Whittington's script apart in favor of \"new ideas\". ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' claims that despite a \"challenged production\" there were no fights for power and no competing cuts for the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/behind-robert-downey-jrs-dolittle-debacle-1272759 |title=\"I Have Some New Ideas\": The Scramble Behind Robert Downey Jr.'s ''Dolittle'' Debacle |last=Kit |first=Borys |last2=McClintock |first2=Pamela |date=January 31, 2020 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> In August 2019, it was reported that the film's title had been changed from ''The Voyage of Doctor Dolittle'' to simply ''Dolittle''.<ref name=\"VT\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vitalthrills.com/2019/08/12/dolittle-synopsis-new-title-january-release/ |title=Dolittle Synopsis and New Title for the January Release |last=Parlevliet |first=Mirko |date=2019-08-12 |website=VitalThrills.com |language=en-US |access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, [[Robert Downey Jr]] discussed on [[Joe Rogan]]'s podcast (''The Joe Rogan Experience'') that the premise of the Dr. Dolittle character in his film stemmed from a [[Culture of Wales|Welsh]] neo-pagan physician called [[William Price (physician)|William Price]]. In the podcast he said: \n\"Same way I did with Iron Man.. all right there's something here and then before I signed on, I was just googling 'weirdest Welsh doctor', I just wanted to think of, I don't want to just do another English accent.. so there was this guy called William Price, who's a nutty Welsh doctor, he was a neo-druidist, he believed that he could communicate with all nature and all that stuff, so I sent a picture of this wild looking guy wearing this kind of suit with stars on it and like a staff in his hand, so I sent that to Gaghan and he goes, \"That looks good to me\" and I was like \"great let's do this movie\"\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d5XTDmm0KUQ |title=Joe Rogan Experience #1411 - Robert Downey Jr. |date=2020-01-15 |publisher=YouTube |access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nMusic artist [[Sia (musician)|Sia]] performed a new song of hers called \"[[Original (Sia song)|Original]]\" for the end credits, while Danny Elfman composed the film's score.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZBEUQjt1-iE |title=Sia - Original (from Dolittle Soundtrack) |date=2020-01-09 |publisher=YouTube |access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was originally going to be released on May 24, 2019, by [[Universal Pictures]] but was moved to April 12, 2019, to avoid competition with ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker]]'' (which was later moved to December 20, 2019). The film was later moved again to January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/doctor-dolittle-movie-delayed-2020/|title=Robert Downey Jr's Doctor Dolittle Movie Delayed to January 2020|date=October 1, 2018|work=Screen Rant}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Dolittle'' was released on [[Digital HD]] on March 24, 2020 and was released on [[DVD]], [[Blu-ray]], and [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]] on April 7, 2020. <ref name=\"DVDsReleaseDates\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/8968/dolittle |title=Dolittle DVD Release Date |website=DVDs Release Dates |language=en |access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2020|3|19|df=US}}, ''Dolittle'' has grossed $77 million in the United States and Canada, and $146.3 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $227.9 million, against a production budget of $175 million.<ref name=\"BOM\" /><ref name=\"NUM\" /> Due to its high production and marketing costs, the film will need to gross around $500 million in order to [[break even]];<ref>{{Cite news |last=Katz |first=Brandon |url=https://observer.com/2019/12/2020-movie-release-schedule-box-office-bombs-prediction/ |title=Which Movies Are Most Likely to Bomb in 2020? |date=December 31, 2019 |work=[[The New York Observer]] |access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> following its debut weekend, it was estimated the film would lose the studio between $50\u2013100 million.<ref name=opening/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/robert-downey-jrs-dolittle-could-lose-100-million-at-box-office/ |title=Robert Downey Jr's 'Dolittle' Could Lose $100 Million at Box Office |last=Jeremy Fuster |date=January 19, 2020 |website=[[TheWrap]] |access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was projected to gross $20\u201322 million from 4,155 theaters in its opening weekend, and a total of around $27 million over the four-day [[Martin Luther King Jr. Day]] weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/01/bad-boys-for-life-dolittle-will-smith-robert-downey-jr-1917-oscar-nominations-box-office-1202831808/ |title=Can 'Bad Boys For Life' Keep The Sony Franchise Alive? \u2013 Box Office Preview\n|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author= Anthony D'Alessandro |accessdate=January 15, 2020|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/can-bad-boys-for-life-succeed-for-sony-where-mib-international-failed/ |title=Can 'Bad Boys for Life' Succeed for Sony Where 'MIB: International' Failed? |last=Jeremy Fuster |date=January 14, 2020 |publisher=[[TheWrap]] |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> It made $6.3 million on its first day, including $925,000 from Thursday night previews. It went on to debut to $22 million (and $29.5 million over the four-day frame), finishing third behind fellow newcomer ''[[Bad Boys for Life]]'' and holdover ''[[1917 (2019 film)|1917]]''.<ref name=\"opening\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/bad-boys-for-life-dolittle-1917-weekend-box-office-1202833726/ |title=How Sony Built 'Bad Boys For Life' Into A Success With $101M+ WW & $73M+ U.S.; 'Dolittle' Poised For $50M+ Loss \u2013 Monday Update |last=Anthony D'Alessandro |date=January 21, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=January 20, 2020}}</ref> The film made $12.1 million in its second weekend and $7.7 million in its third, remaining in third both times.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/bad-boys-for-life-the-gentleman-the-turning-weekend-box-office-1202840184/ |title='Bad Boys For Life' & '1917' Shooting Past $100M; 'The Turning' Slammed With Second 'F' Of 2020 |last=Anthony D'Alessandro |date=January 24, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/01/gretel-hansel-finds-475k-the-rhythm-section-offbeat-with-235k-thursday-night-previews-1202847821/ |title='Bad Boys For Life' Scores Over Super Bowl Weekend With $17M+; 'Rhythm Section' Is A Mess\n|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=February 2, 2020|date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film held an approval rating of 15% based on 212 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 3.85/10. The website's critics consensus reads, \"''Dolittle'' may be enough to entertain very young viewers, but they deserve better than this rote adaptation's jumbled story and stale humor.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dolittle/ |title=Dolittle (2020) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film had a weighted average score of 26 out of 100, based on 46 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dolittle |title=Dolittle Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported a viewer average of 3 out of 5 stars.<ref name=opening/>\n\nCourtney Howard of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the film a \"frenetic, crass kids' flick\" and wrote: \"What should have been an awe-filled adventure quickly curdles into an awful one, thanks to a pedestrian formula and the filmmakers' fixation on fart jokes.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/reviews/dolittle-review-1203467269/ |title='Dolittle': Film Review |last=Courtney Howard |date=January 15, 2020 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', [[Todd McCarthy]] said that \"From the very first scene, it's clear something is terribly off with this lavishly misbegotten attempt to repopularize an animal-loaded literary franchise that was born exactly a century ago. The oddly diffident star and executive producer Robert Downey Jr. never finds the power-supplying third rail needed to energize a tale that fails to make a real case for being reinterpreted\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/dolittle-review-1269681 |title='Dolittle': Film Review |last=Todd McCarthy |date=January 15, 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBritish film critic [[Mark Kermode]] gave the film a negative review, saying, \"Terrible script. Terrible visuals. Dull plot. Dismal gags. The fact that at 101 minutes it really tested one's patience. It is shockingly poor.\" He particularly criticized Robert Downey Jr.'s attempt at a Welsh accent, calling it \"something from Mars.\"<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1iEIHsv3jkY |title=Dolittle reviewed by Mark Kermode |date=February 7, 2020 |access-date=2020-02-11 |medium=video |via=YouTube}}</ref> In examining the films ending, Douglas Laman of ''[[Screen Rant]]'' noted that the film as a whole suffered from numerous problems, including \"...Dolittle's new backstory involving a deceased wife...the largely lifeless voice-over work of the animal characters [and] its painfully unfunny comedy.\" <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/dolittle-movie-ending-bad-explained/ |title=Dolittle Movie Ending Explained: Why It's So Bad |last=Douglas Laman |date=March 30, 2020 |website=[[Screen Rant]] |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{Doctor Dolittle}}\n{{Stephen Gaghan}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020 fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s children's adventure films]]\n[[Category:2020s children's fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Doctor Dolittle films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about animals]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Stephen Gaghan]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Danny Elfman]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1819]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Shepperton Studios]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Wales]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Stephen Gaghan]]\n[[Category:Motion capture in film]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "86.158.34.242", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCast)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dolittle_(film)"}
{"title_page": "The Timeless Children", "text_new": "{{Infobox Doctor Who episode\n| number             = 295b\n| serial_name        = The Timeless Children\n| show               = DW\n| type               = episode\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| doctor             = [[Jodie Whittaker]] ([[Thirteenth Doctor]])\n| companions         = \n* [[Bradley Walsh]] ([[Graham O'Brien]])\n* [[Tosin Cole]] ([[Ryan Sinclair]])\n* [[Mandip Gill]] ([[Yasmin Khan (Doctor Who)|Yasmin Khan]])\n| guests             = \n* [[Sacha Dhawan]] \u2013 [[The Master (Doctor Who)|The Master]]\n* [[Patrick O'Kane]] \u2013 Ashad\n* [[Ian McElhinney]] \u2013 Ko Sharmus\n* [[Julie Graham]] \u2013 Ravio\n* Alex Austin \u2013 Yedlarmi\n* Matt Carver \u2013 Ethan\n* Rhiannon Clements \u2013 Bescot\n* Seylan Baxter \u2013 Tecteun\n* Kirsty Besterman \u2013 Solpado\n* [[Paul Kasey]] \u2013 [[Judoon]] Captain\n* [[Nicholas Briggs]] \u2013 Voice of [[Cybermen]] & Judoon Captain\n* Matthew Rohman \u2013 Cyberman\n* Simon Carew \u2013 Cyberman\n* Jon Davey \u2013 Cyberman\n* Richard Highgate \u2013 Cyberman\n* Richard Price \u2013 Cyberman\n* Mickey Lewis \u2013 Cyberman\n* Matthew Doman \u2013 Cyberman\n* Paul Bailey \u2013 Cyberman\n* [[Jo Martin]] \u2013 [[The Doctor (Doctor Who)|The Doctor]]\n<!-- Please do not change these credits from how they are set out, including name of characters, as these are listed as they were in the episode's closing credits -->\n| director           = [[Jamie Magnus Stone]]\n| writer             = [[Chris Chibnall]]\n| script_editor      = Fiona McAllister\n| producer           = [[Nikki Wilson]]\n| executive_producer = {{Unbulleted list|Chris Chibnall|Matt Strevens}}\n| composer           = [[Segun Akinola]]\n| series             = [[Doctor Who (series 12)|Series 12]]\n| length             = 2nd of 2-part story, 65 minutes\n| date               = {{Start date|2020|3|1|df=y}}\n| preceding          = \"[[Ascension of the Cybermen]]\"\n| following          = <!--Per the template documentation, nothing should be added here until a non draft article actually exists for the next episode. Wikipedia is not an indiscriminate listing of information. Such additions WILL be reverted.-->\n}}\n\n\"'''The Timeless Children'''\" is the tenth and final episode of the [[Doctor Who (series 12)|twelfth series]] of the British [[science fiction]] television programme ''[[Doctor Who]]'', first broadcast on [[BBC One]] on 1 March 2020. It was written by [[Chris Chibnall]], and directed by [[Jamie Magnus Stone]]. It is the second of a two-part story; the previous episode, \"[[Ascension of the Cybermen]]\", aired on 23 February.\n\nThe episode stars [[Jodie Whittaker]] as the [[Thirteenth Doctor]], alongside [[Bradley Walsh]], [[Tosin Cole]], and [[Mandip Gill]] as her [[Companion (Doctor Who)|companion]]s, Graham O'Brien, Ryan Sinclair and Yasmin Khan, respectively. The episode also stars [[Sacha Dhawan]] as [[The Master (Doctor Who)|The Master]].\n\nThe episode was watched by 4.69 million viewers, and received mixed reviews from critics. The concept of the Timeless Child and how it impacts the Doctor's origins has been very divisive among fans.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe Master persuades the Doctor to join him on [[Gallifrey]], where he forces her to enter [[the Matrix (Doctor Who)|the Matrix]]. He shows her the secret history of Gallifrey and its native Shobogans. Tecteun, a space explorer, found a \"timeless child\" with infinite capacity to [[regeneration (Doctor Who)|regenerate]]. She adopted the child and studied her, successfully grafting her regeneration capacity into the Shobogans, transforming them into Time Lords; they chose to limit a Time Lord's regenerations to twelve. The Master reveals that the Doctor is the \"timeless child\". Tecteun and the child were inducted into a clandestine organisation called the Division, the details of which were redacted from the Matrix. The Doctor's memories were subsequently erased, prior to the childhood she remembers; only snippets remain, masked as the story of the Irish policeman Brendan. \n\nWith the Doctor trapped in the Matrix, the Master lures Ashad to Gallifrey and shrinks him with his tissue compression eliminator, taking the Cyberium. With its knowledge and the bodies of the Time Lords he had killed on his arrival to Gallifrey, the Master creates a race of infinitely-regenerating Cybermen, aiming to use them to take over the universe. In the Matrix, a vision of the previously unseen Doctor from  \"Fugitive Of The Judoon\" restores the Doctor\u2019s belief in herself. The Doctor escapes by overloading the Matrix with all of her memories from her past incarnations.\n\nOn board the Cyber-carrier, Bescot is killed, while Yaz and Graham successfully hide from the invading Cybermen in empty Cyber-armor. They subsequently save the lives of Ryan, Ethan, and Ko Sharmus from Cybermen forces sent to the planet by Ashad. The group gather and agree to go through the portal to Gallifrey.\n\nThe Doctor regroups with her companions, and discovers Ashad's minaturised body contains a \"Death Particle\" capable of destroying all organic life on a planet. The Doctor and her friends blow up the Cyber-carrier, destroying Ashad's army in the process and foiling his plot to rebuild the Cyber-Empire. Finding unused TARDISes, she programs one to take her allies home. The Doctor takes one of Ko Sharmus' explosives to set off the particle. She is unable to trigger it when goaded by the Master, but Ko Sharmus appears and takes it, as penance for failing to suitably hide the Cyberium. The Doctor escapes in another TARDIS as the explosion consumes Gallifrey.\n\nThe Doctor's allies arrive on contemporary Earth in their TARDIS. The Doctor lands the other TARDIS near her own, but as she prepares to take off, she is arrested by the [[Judoon]] and teleported to a prison located inside an asteroid.\n\n===Continuity===\nAs the Doctor broadcasts her memories to escape the Matrix, the show uses numerous scenes from both the new series and the old, featuring each Doctor, several companions, and villains. Notably the flashback includes ''[[The Brain of Morbius]]'', a [[Fourth Doctor]] serial. In that story, while the Doctor and Morbius are hooked to a machine during a battle of wits, the machine briefly flashed up the former regenerations of the Doctor and several additional faces, then implied to be previous versions of the Doctor (in actuality, faces of some of the production crew). ''The Brain of Morbius'' producer Philip Hinchcliffe (who also played one of said faces) had said that was the implication of that scene then, but as they wrote in the twelve-regeneration limit, it became difficult to write that in future episodes and eventually became considered that these were in fact faces of Morbius. This scene from ''The Brain of Morbius'' is shown during the Doctor's flashback in this episode, finally identifying these as the faces of incarnations of the Timeless Child.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-03-01/doctor-who-more-doctors-morbius/ | title = Doctor Who\u2019s big reveal just solved a 44-year-old mystery | first = Morgan | last=  Jeffrey | date = 1 March 2020 | accessdate = 1 March 2020 | work = [[Radio Times]] }}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\n\"The Timeless Children\" was written by [[Chris Chibnall]].<ref name=\"ChibnallEpisodes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/doctor-who/69159/doctor-who-series-12-will-start-and-end-with-two-parters|title=Doctor Who Series 12 will start and end with two-parters|date=27 December 2019|website=Denofgeek|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"DWM 548\">{{cite web |url=https://cultbox.co.uk/general/doctor-who-magazine-reveals-titles-of-two-part-series-finale |title=Doctor Who Magazine reveals titles of two-part series finale |last=Laford |first=Andrew |publisher=Cultbox |date=6 February 2020 |accessdate=6 February 2020 }}</ref> Further episode details were announced in ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'' #548 in early February 2020.<ref name=\"DWM 548\" />\n\n=== Casting ===\n\n[[Julie Graham]] was cast as Ravio in the episode.<ref name=\"DWM 548\" /> [[Ian McElhinney]] and [[Steve Toussaint]] were announced as guest stars in the two-part finale, \"Ascension of the Cybermen\" / \"The Timeless Children\"; however, Toussaint did not appear in this episode after his character was killed in the events of \"Ascension of the Cybermen\".<ref name=\"Toussaint\">{{cite web|url= https://cultbox.co.uk/news/ian-mcelhinney-and-steve-toussaint-to-guest-star-in-doctor-who-series-finale|title=Doctor Who Series 12: Ian McElhinney and Steve Toussaint to star in Doctor Who|date= 6 February 2020|website=CultBox|accessdate= 8 February 2020}}</ref> Jo Martin reprises her role from \"[[Fugitive of the Judoon]]\" as a regeneration of the Doctor.\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Jamie Magnus Stone]] directed the fifth block of the ninth and tenth episodes.<ref name=\"Directors\">{{cite web|url=http://cultbox.co.uk/news/doctor-who-series-12-new-directors-discovered|title=Doctor Who Series 12: new directors discovered|date=20 May 2019|website=CultBox}}</ref>\n\n== Broadcast and reception ==\n{{TV ratings\n| aggregatenosort = y\n| aggregate1 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Tomatometer)\n| aggregate1score = 71%<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/doctor_who/s12/e10|title=Doctor Who - Season 12 Episode 10|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n| aggregate2 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Average Score)\n| aggregate2score = 6.33/10<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\" />\n| rev1 = [[The A.V. Club]]\n| rev1score = B<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tv.avclub.com/doctor-who-s-season-finale-raises-more-questions-than-i-1842008722|title=Doctor Who\u2019s season finale raises more questions than it answers|first=Caroline |last=Siede |date=1 March 2020 |website=The A.V. Club}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2score = B+<REF>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/recaps/doctor-who-season-12-episode-10/|title=Doctor Who season finale recap: The Timeless Child, revealed|first=Devan |last=Coggan |date=1 March 2020 |website=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/01/doctor-series-12-episode-10-review-timeless-children-rewrites-history-books-literally-12330619/ |title=Doctor Who series 12 finale The Timeless Children rewrites history books &#124; Metro News |publisher=Metro.co.uk |date=2020-02-14 |accessdate=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n| rev4 = [[Radio Times]]\n| rev4score = {{stars|2|5}}<ref name=\"radio times review\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-03-02/doctor-who-the-timeless-children-review/|title=Doctor Who The Timeless Children review: the much-vaunted finale is an overblown gush of nonsense|first=Patrick|last=Mulkern|publisher=Radio Times|date=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Ed Power |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/doctor-who-review-final-episode-10-timeless-children-jodie-whittaker-master-cybermen-a9367326.html |title=Doctor Who review, The Timeless Children: There\u2019s so much going on it becomes overwhelming |publisher=The Independent |date= |accessdate=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n| rev6 = [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]\n| rev6score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Hogan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2020/03/01/doctor-whothe-timeless-children-review-giddy-baffling-rush-finale/ |title=Doctor Who: The Timeless Children, review: a giddy, baffling rush of a finale |publisher=Telegraph.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n}}\n\n=== Television ===\n\"The Timeless Children\" aired on 1 March 2020.<ref name=\"DWM 548\" /> It is the second of a two-part story; the previous episode, \"[[Ascension of the Cybermen]]\", aired on 23 February.<ref name=\"DWM 548\" />\n\n=== Ratings ===\n\"The Timeless Children\" was watched by 3.78 million viewers overnight, making it the seventh most watched programme for the day in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2020/03/doctor-who-timeless-children-was.html |title=The Timeless Children - Overnight Viewing Figures |work=Doctor Who News |last=Marcus |date=2 March 2020 |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> The episode had an [[Audience Appreciation|Audience Appreciation Index]] score of 82.<ref name=\"Official Ratings\" /> The episode received an official total of 4.69 million viewers across all UK channels and was the 30th most-watched programme of the week.<ref name=\"Official Ratings\">{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2020/03/timeless-child-official-ratings.html |title=The Timeless Children - Official Ratings |work=Doctor Who News |last=Marcus |date=9 March 2020 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> It was the lowest-rated episode of the show since its revival in 2005 after \"[[The Eaters of Light]]\" in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/09/doctor-season-12-ends-lowest-ratings-since-2005-reboot-12373071/|title=Doctor Who season 12 ends on lowest ratings since 2005 reboot|date=2020-03-09|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nThe episode received a 71% approval, and an average rating of 6.33/10, on the review aggregate site [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 14 reviews from critics. The consensus on the website reads, \"Its relentless plotting and exposition teeter on overwhelming, but a bold daringness to reinvent Whovian lore coupled with Jodie Whittaker's dynamic performance make 'The Timeless Children' a successful season finale.\"<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote|Thirteenth Doctor}}\n* {{BBCDWnew||m000g09m|The Timeless Children}}\n* {{TardisIndexFile|The Timeless Childr